      <title>Latinos are the fastest-growing fanbase in the NFL. What's the league's playbook?</title>
      <author>Alan Chazaro</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2024/12/21/g-s1-38443/latinos-growing-fanbase-nfl</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2024/12/21/g-s1-38443/latinos-growing-fanbase-nfl</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2024/12/21/g-s1-38443/latinos-growing-fanbase-nfl</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 21 Dec 2024 11:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;div id="resg-s1-39220" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4323;         --source-height: 2882;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/1100/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" class="img" type="image/webp" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" data-format="webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/1100/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" class="img" type="image/jpeg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" data-format="jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/1100/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" class="img" alt="Fans cheer before an NFL football game between the Los Angeles Chargers and the Kansas City Chiefs, Monday, Nov. 18, 2019, in Mexico City." data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4323x2882+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2Ffd%2F08cbceae465c966561412f05a099%2Fap22318756654144.jpg" data-format="jpeg" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Fans cheer before an NFL football game between the Los Angeles Chargers and the Kansas City Chiefs in Mexico City in 2019. The NFL plans to play as many as eight international games beginning next season. The NFL's two largest international markets are Mexico and Brazil,                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Rebecca Blackwell/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Raúl Allegre arrived in Washington state from Torreón, Coahuila, in 1977 as a high school foreign exchange student. The school's football coach immediately noticed the Mexican fútbolero, who had an aptitude for using his foot. That season, as a senior, Allegre learned how to kick a football for the first time.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Historically, Mexican immigrants haven't always embraced the U.S. pigskin sport, known in Mexico as simply "Americano." Even rarer? That a teenage Mexican citizen in the 70s would have any desire — let alone pathway — to play in the National Football League.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39223" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3143;         --source-height: 2153;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3143x2153+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fba%2F93%2F36eb057547dfab572e1ec7b238be%2Fap535353806408-1.jpg" class="img" alt="Seth Joyner (not shown) of the Philadelphia Eagles blocks a field goal attempt by kicker Raul Allegre (2) of the New York Giants, as Andre Waters (20) also makes a diving effort at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J., Dec. 6, 1987. Allegre later kicked a 28-yard field goal to give the Giants a 23-20 win over the Eagles." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Raul Allegre (2), shown here attempting a field goal against the Philadelphia Eagles in 1987, is the most decorated Mexican-born kicker in NFL history. He won two Super Bowls as the star booter for the New York Giants in 1987 and '91 en route to a nine-season career.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          G. Paul Burnett/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Allegre went on to become the most decorated Mexican-born kicker in NFL history, eventually winning two Super Bowls as the star booter for the New York Giants in 1987 and '91 en route to a nine-season career.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;Though he wasn't the first Mexican-born player to suit up on the gridiron — that was Tom Fears, a wide receiver from Guadalajara who led the league in receptions after being drafted to the Los Angeles Rams in 1948 — Allegre was certainly one of the very few to make it across the border and onto the field.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39224" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2560;         --source-height: 3150;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2560x3150+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F19%2Fae%2F66aa0710493984bebfe4471b4821%2Fap81859564231.jpg" class="img" alt="The Los Angeles Rams high-powered passing combination, probably football&amp;#039;s best, gets together at Redlands, Calif., as the NFL titleholders began drills July 23, 1952. From left: quarterback Bob Waterfield and ends Elroy Hirsch and Tom Fears." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The Los Angeles Rams high-powered passing combination, probably football's best, gets together at Redlands, Calif., as the NFL titleholders began drills July 23, 1952. From left: quarterback Bob Waterfield and ends Elroy Hirsch and Tom Fears.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Harold Filan/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;"The NFL hadn't internationalized back then," says Allegre. "Today, the market in Mexico and Latin America is enormous. That didn't exist in the '70s when I was growing up. There were some Latinos like Tom Flores, Max Montoya, Anthony Muñoz. But even then, many of the Latino players didn't register as Latinos."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39226" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3078;         --source-height: 2062;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3078x2062+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe0%2Fa7%2Ff3d6798448279473f0e75a5a8101%2Fap8109010853.jpg" class="img" alt="Members of the Cincinnati Bengals offensive line include wide receiver Steve Kreider (86), right guard Max Montoya (65) and left tackle Anthony Munoz (78) during an NFL game early in the football season of 1981. Location unknown." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Members of the Cincinnati Bengals offensive line include wide receiver Steve Kreider (86), right guard Max Montoya (65) and left tackle Anthony Munoz (78) during an NFL game in 1981.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;In 2024, that's no longer the case. The NFL is beginning to shift its league's perception — formerly as one of American pride, militarism, and rigid conservatism (see: the backlash on Colin Kaepernick's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-protests-for-racial-justice/2020/06/05/871290906/nfl-on-kneeling-players-protests-we-were-wrong-commissioner-says" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;infamous kneel&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; in 2016) — to one of global inclusivity, community values and mindfulness (see: the Washington Commanders &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2022/02/02/1077365060/washington-commanders-football-team-new-name" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;changing their franchise name and logo&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; in 2020). It hasn't been a perfect transition, but it's clear the NFL is seizing an opportunity to re-brand and reach more fans, especially outside of the States.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;In November during an NFL game in Germany, commissioner Roger Goodell stated the league would like to play as many as eight international games beginning next season. Currently, the NFL's two largest international markets are Mexico and Brazil, with a reported 39.5 and 35.9 million fans, respectively. Germany, China and the United Kingdom round out the top five, each with less than 20 million supporters.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;In terms of overall viewership growth, Latinos lead the way. League sources confirmed Latino viewers (both English- and Spanish-speaking) have spiked by 11%. Spanish broadcasts alone have jumped 34% compared to previous years. Those numbers are good enough to outpace any other demographic of measurable fan growth.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;This Christmas, Netflix México has announced its first-ever &lt;a href="https://www.netflix.com/tudum/articles/nfl-games-on-netflix" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;live stream of NFL games&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. So what happened between the time when Allegre first took aim at the uprights as one of the few Latin American-born players of his day until now — when multiple Latino-heritage players, as well as a diverse array of Spanish-speaking fans, have joined the NFL's ranks?&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;NFL en español&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;The NFL hasn't always translated easily to fans outside of the States. In fact, it required an entirely new vocabulary to be learned by non-English speaking audiences.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-38443-100" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col"&gt;                     &lt;!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" --&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;!-- END ID="RESG-S1-38443-100" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " --&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Fernando Von Rossum is credited with literally translating the game for Spanish-only fans. Throughout 60 years, he announced NFL games for Mexican broadcast networks. Von Rossum's groundlaying work led to being honored by the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio. Earlier this year he became the first and only Spanish-speaking recipient of the prestigious &lt;a href="https://www.profootballhof.com/news/2024/06/fernando-von-rossum-selected-to-receive-ralph-hay-pioneer-award-from-hall-of-fame/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ralph Hay Pioneer Award&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. In Mexico, he's viewed as the godfather of NFL fandom.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"What's a quarterback? There is no word for that in Spanish. So he called it the 'mariscal de campo'," says Antonio Ramos, a Mexican-born broadcaster in Spanish for the Carolina Panthers. "A fumble? That's 'balon suelto.' He basically tropicalized every NFL term without losing its essence, so we could understand it and make it our own."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;In an era when the NFL didn't have much of a global presence, Von Rossum expanded the game's accessibility for Spanish-speaking fanatics. He's the reason football became more familiar, and more interesting, to generations of Latin Americans, including both Ramos and Allegre.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;Unlike the U.S., where English-language NFL games are shown multiple times a week, Spanish-speaking fans haven't traditionally had that viewership luxury. To put things in perspective, Telemundo became the first Spanish broadcast network in the U.S. to&lt;a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaellore/2023/01/17/nfl-partners-with-ngl-collective-to-grow-its-latino-fanbase/?sh=60c8d95d596a" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt; air the Super Bowl exclusively in Spanish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. That was in 2022.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39221" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5472;         --source-height: 3648;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5472x3648+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F56%2F91%2F6a1a9f0e47f8a3ebb0aae23baf46%2Fap22318756639611.jpg" class="img" alt="The flags of Mexico and the United States cover the field before an NFL football game between the Los Angeles Chargers and the Kansas City Chiefs Monday, Nov. 18, 2019, in Mexico City. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The flags of Mexico and the United States cover the field before an NFL football game between the Los Angeles Chargers and the Kansas City Chiefs Nov. 18, 2019, in Mexico City.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Eduardo Verdugo/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Since then, &lt;a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaellore/2023/01/17/nfl-partners-with-ngl-collective-to-grow-its-latino-fanbase/?sh=60c8d95d596a" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;the NFL has inked multiple deals with Spanish-speaking networks&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, and regularly airs games in Mexico and countries throughout Latin America. The league even hosts annual games in places like Mexico City and São Paulo, Brazil.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Ramos never imagined that as a child. He could only watch certain games on special occasions and says he learned the rules of football by playing &lt;em&gt;NFL Madden&lt;/em&gt; — the popular video game franchise — as a teenager in Mexico. Now, Ramos is six seasons into his career with the Carolina Panthers (a team that, coincidentally, boasts &lt;a href="https://x.com/panthers/status/1846331072658760161?s=46" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;the league's only Latino-heritage head coach in Dave Canales&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, as of this writing). Though backing the Panthers might still be an aberration in Mexico (most fans cheer for legacy teams like the Dallas Cowboys or Pittsburgh Steelers), Ramos' is adamant the league has made significant strides to reach a new generation of foreign NFL proponents like him.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39227" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 8640;         --source-height: 5760;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8640x5760+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fde%2F0f%2F048640074201bd7f4eb615f7828b%2Fap24302193423166.jpg" class="img" alt="Carolina Panthers head coach Dave Canales talks to referees before an NFL football game against the Denver Broncos Sunday, Oct. 27, 2024, in Denver. (AP Photo/Jack Dempsey)" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The Carolina Panthers' Dave Canales, the league's only Latino-heritage head coach, talks to referees before an NFL game against the Denver Broncos in October.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Jack Dempsey/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;"I feel like [Latino appreciation] is real now. It's not just &lt;a href="https://latino.si.edu/learn/teaching-and-learning-resources/hispanic-heritage-month-resources/hispanic-heritage-month" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hispanic Heritage Month&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; or treated as a joke," says Ramos. "Teams are really investing in stadium production and the community like I've never seen, not just marketing with a few advertisements or social media posts in Spanish. This is constant and permanent and you see Latinos have more of a voice now. It's genuine."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-38443-101" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col"&gt;                     &lt;!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" --&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;!-- END ID="RESG-S1-38443-101" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " --&gt;    &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's NFL is "Por La Cultura"&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;For the modern sports fan, watching the NFL — let alone any league in any country — is more attainable than ever. With the internet, social media apps, and a slew of streaming services, fans no longer have to be stateside to know who Aaron Rodgers or Lamar Jackson is. This accessibility has allowed the NFL to reach a larger Spanish segment.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Since 2019, Javier Farfan has been the quarterback — or, &lt;em&gt;el mariscal de campo&lt;/em&gt; — overseeing a massive push to highlight the league-wide spectrum of Latinidad.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;A New York-raised Ecuadorian-American, Farfan initially joined the NFL as their Global Brand and Consumer Marketing Consultant. For Latino-heritage players and fans — whether Spanish-speaking, English-speaking, or bilingual — having Farfan lead the charge has been game-changing.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-39230" class="bucketwrap image x-large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4462;         --source-height: 2975;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4462x2975+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d%2F85%2F9b3aa2854eb697eb73c3645b6dd0%2Fap23331026175900.jpg 1800w" data-template="htt